AGI - "Today we celebrate 90 years of achievements but look at the new challenges we face and that together we will be able to face to achieve other important results." This was said by the Minister of Health, Orazio Schillaci, in his speech at the ceremony for the 90 years of the Higher Institute of Health (Iss) in the presence of the President of the Republic, Sergio Mattarella>.
&nbsp;
"In the course of these nine decades - it has emphasized Schillaci - the Institute has faced so many challenges contributing in a meaningful way to improve the life of the Italians and to support the health policies of our nation. It is really a reason for great pride in the Ministry of Health, and for the National Health Service, to have a technical-scientific organ that produces excellent research > and enjoys a prestige conquered beyond our borders, thanks to the women and men who carry out their activities, among which I remember that there are also four Nobel Prizes >".
&nbsp;
&nbsp;Schillaci underlined that Iss is a "national reference point for research, control, technical and scientific advice and also for training, since its birth" recalling how it "affirmed institutions in facing the great health emergencies that, in almost a century, invested Italy, from malaria to cholera in 1973, from Seveso to Covid".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"We live in an era - the minister has continued - marked by a progress of knowledge increasingly fast and able to direct in a straight way the choices we operate for our future. And so today, perhaps even more than yesterday, the activity of the Institute is crucial to support us in facing the great challenges we face. And it is so much more in a 'one health' perspective that must be the basis of health policies, so that we can take into account at all times the stringent correlation between human health, animal and the environment in which we live. In this key - it has explained - there is a project that offers a clear picture of this substantial link between the research activities that lead today and our tomorrow. I think of the project 'Sea Care', designed to investigate the health of seas around the world with the use, for the first time, of a standardized method. On board these ships there are young researchers who work with the bow really directed towards the future, because &nbsp; to guard it will be fundamental the balance of the ecosystem".
&nbsp;
"I am convinced that events such as this should serve to increase awareness of how important it is to focus on research, innovation and valorisation of our best resources," Schillaci concluded.
